So red, we have fire---that's correlated with desire. The idea here is that there's pure cognizance, just like a dream without... before a dream...  Let's say a dream has no content, it would just be a pure cognizance. So in that respect, it's called Buddha Amitabha when it's enlightened, when it's pure. There's an aspect called Amitabha, because that's discernment. See, as we rest naturally and in pure wisdom light, there's natural discernment there. 

Ratnasambhava is a natural equality. Vairochana, there's natural wisdom of Dharmadhatu, so the all-phenomena. Amoghasiddhi is the wisdom of all-accomplishing, and Akshobhya is mirror-like wisdom. Okay?

When mirror-like wisdom gets distorted and formed, you have the color blue, which makes space from anger. So not the kind of anger where you're out "da-da-da!" [sounds of anger] Yes, that too, but just like fire can be fire in your digestive system, anger is a subtle part. Okay? Anger has a subtle part that constructs elements. So think of it... of anger as a separator, as a stubbornness---we get into stupors sometimes, angry stupors. Space is the element that's created from that part of our mind--that's anger.

Air is created by a part of our... now remember, anger and jealousy, these are incredibly reductive words. I feel like we should have more scientific words for these aspects of cognizance. These are actually distorted lucid aspects of cognizance.

So you have, well how can we get a little more scientific with anger for example? We would say the divisive aspect of cognizance manifests space. And in regards to jealousy, we would say that's an aspect of cognizance that creates air so it's also divisive, very close to anger actually. But I'm not going to redefine all these, but you know, to me these are elementary words here. Ignorance creates water---water is considered foundational, so is ignorance. Pride, yellow---the color yellow creates earth. Desire creates fire, that one might be more obvious with red.

And by the way, all these colors are proven to have deep psychological effects in modern science; just look in modern psychology, which makes it even more perverted that corporations, like McDonald's, will use yellow and red, yeah. Because not only do they have to do with desire and pride, but they also have to do with inflammation and disease. Yeah where blues are more healing and things like that.

So really, these corporations that take advantage of these psychological advantages of colors, or the psychological aspects of colors, this is a deep, deep perversion, because you cannot do that unless the people know. Alright? They need to consent to the stuff.

So anytime a company, corporation, person, teacher, school, religious leader---anytime they're using some psychological technique that you don't know that they're using---this is unfair. This is abuse; a deep kind of abuse---a divine abuse, a cosmic law you're violating. So, if you see my YouTube video... stop it, McDonald's CEOs that are watching Dzogchen videos, you guys, stop it.

Okay so that's a really, you know, element-kind of reductive, very simplified explanation of all this. It's something that one has to see within your own awareness, please don't turn it into a belief system. It's dangerous with that because we're dealing with existential things here. But at the same time, it's also very important to understand the creative power of your mind. You awareness holders that are getting deeper into the practice, start trying it out---start thinking a certain way and see if it affects your reality. Yeah. Do it in a responsible, skillful way, I think it's okay.

For example, I put a lot of juice into Luna yesterday, into her healing. I put a lot of doing yogi stuff, like mantras and moon practices and all this, and today I wake up and her gums are looking pink again. I can't believe it, the miracle worked so fast. But I'm still taking her to the vet Monday. Okay? But yeah I can't believe it, yeah, they were so inflamed on both sides. Now, I was also putting salt water on them, rinsing them, so I don't know what it did. That's how it should be with our healing, don't be afraid to use reality as you're healing, like saltwater, Epsom baths, medicine, all this stuff; but incorporate your mind into that.

See there has to be harmony, always, if you want things to work. So if we want to heal, it's our thinking mind that gets aligned with our practices and our emotions. When all that is aligned, I feel like we can maneuver some healing. Yeah. If you're taking medicine and your saying, "This shit's never gonna work" (aww, there goes the recording; well, just leave it).

But if you're taking it... really, that's kind of placebo/nocebo, right? If you're taking this medicine and the rest of your mind is not aligned with that, then you will probably create some hindrances in that respect. But if we can manage to align what we're doing with what we're thinking and feeling, this is pretty powerful stuff.

And I'm not an expert everybody, okay? So you explore it with me; and whatever realizations you have, I invite you to share them as a kind of science and new grounds here that we're exploring, okay?

So that's my short explanation of the elements and the colors, and the five Buddha families, and how they relate. By the way, those numbers you see there are the eight consciousnesses. You have the five sense consciousnesses, the sixth emotional-thinking consciousness, the seventh ego consciousness, and the eighth is the alaya seeded with karma.

So that was all from memory too, so I'm sure I was missing something I probably would have wanted to mention. But anyway, I hope that benefits. And what seems to be a trend, the person who asked the question is gone so hopefully they will benefit from that, and maybe some of you also.



